---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Roguelike Browser Widget"
  description="A standalone Blazor WebAssembly widget running the C# roguelike engine directly in the browser."
>
  <main class="bg-base-200 px-4 py-16">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl space-y-8">
      <section class="space-y-4">
        <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-secondary">
          Browser-Local
        </p>
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-semibold text-base-content">
          C# roguelike widget with no server session
        </h1>
        <p class="max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-base-content/70">
          This embed is a standalone Blazor WebAssembly app. Each iframe instance
          boots its own in-browser `GameCore` session, so you can drop multiple
          widgets onto a page without managing per-user backend state.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="rounded-[2rem] border border-base-300 bg-base-100 p-4 shadow-sm">
        <iframe
          src="/widgets/roguelike/index.html"
          title="Roguelike browser widget"
          loading="lazy"
          class="h-[980px] w-full rounded-[1.5rem] border-0 bg-[#08111d]"
        ></iframe>
      </section>

      <section class="rounded-[2rem] border border-base-300 bg-base-100 p-6 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-base-content">Embed</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-7 text-base-content/70">
          Once published, the widget can be embedded anywhere with a plain iframe.
        </p>
        <pre class="mt-4 overflow-auto rounded-2xl bg-neutral p-4 text-sm text-neutral-content"><code>{`<iframe
  src="https://your-site.vercel.app/widgets/roguelike/index.html"
  title="Cyberpunk Roguelike Widget"
  width="100%"
  height="980"
  style="border:0;border-radius:24px;overflow:hidden"
></iframe>`}</code></pre>
      </section>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
